%AS bias (distribution near 5'-UTR)
\section{Gene-specific Variables Associated with Retrotransposon Distribution}
%Correlation of Linear Decay with CDS Exon Density
\subsection{Linear Decay of AS Bias is Associated with Coding Sequence Density}
\label{sec:cds}
The linear decay of RTs across gene deciles may be contributed to by a number of factors. The most likely of these is the presence of coding sequence exons (CDS), since these are the most conserved units of a gene. Furthermore, Zhang et. al. showed that RTs were less often located in close proximity to an exon. Therefore the density of CDS within each decile was calculated. Indeed, CDS density increased at a linear rate across gene deciles (figure \ref{fig:cds_noUTR}). The first decile of genes contained more CDS than the second decile.  AS Alu were inversely correlated with this distribution of CDS (R$^{2}$ = -0.94; one-tailed p <  2.64e-05). S Alu, however, were not correlated with CDS (R$^{2}$ = -0.30; one-tailed p = 0.200). These results suggest that AS RTs are highly inversely correlated with CDS exon density.

    %Figure CDS (no secondary 5'-UTR)
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{cds_noUTR.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Distribution of Coding Sequence Exons in RefSeq Genes\\}The number of coding sequence exons (CDS) in the sense orientation were normalized by all sense oriented CDS in RefSeq genes.}}
        \label{fig:cds_noUTR}
    \end{figure}

%Alternative Splicing
\subsection{Alternative Splicing}
Alu and L1 both contain cryptic splice sequences that are often used for alternative splicing. It was therefore investigated whether genes with alternative isoforms have a different AS bias than constitutively expressed genes. Using the knownAlt annotation track from Hg19 (UCSC Genome Browser), we separated genes into those with known alternative splicing events, and those that were constitutively expressed. We found no significant differences between the distribution of AS and S between the two groups (chi-square p > 0.25, p > 0.23 respectively). We further calculated the correlation of AS Alu density and CDS density within alternatively spliced genes. The negative correlation that is seen across all genes was replicated when examining only genes that are alternatively spliced (Pearson’s correlation coefficient: -0.78, p < 0.008). Therefore, there was no observable difference between alternatively spliced and constitutively spliced genes.

%Correlation of Linear Decay with 5'-UTR
\subsection{Alu and L1 are Decreased Near 5\rq-UTR}
Although, previous studies using raw distances showed that RTs were increased near TSSs, here it was noted that AS were increased over S at a ratio less than expected based on the linear trend from the internal deciles. Therefore, although there was an increase near the TSS, this increase was modified by another factor, likely the exon density. As mentioned earlier, the first decile was defined by the TSS and was therefore enriched for the presence of  5\rq-UTR exons (figure \ref{fig:utr_nosecond}), however the presence of a coding exon (CDS) was not obligatory by the normalization procedure (figure \ref{fig:cds_noUTR}). This suggested the possibility that normalizing by the TSS exaggerated an effect of the UTR on RT density. It was therefore important to first study if AS RT density near the TSS was correlated with the presence of the 5\rq-UTR or was due to another variable (e.g: CDS). To accomplish this, the effect of the 5\rq-UTR had to be separated from any latent effects correlated with the first decile. To separate out these effects, genes were identified that contained a second 5\rq-UTR within deciles other than the first decile. These 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs were commonly due to either alternative start positions of transcription, or transcription of a separate gene that began within the boundaries of another gene. Examples of genes that contained 2$^\circ$  5\rq-UTRs are depicted in figure \ref{fig:25utr}. 


    %Figure 5'-UTR in genes with no internal 5'-UTR
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{utr_nosecond.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Distribution of 5\rq-UTRs in genes with no 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs\\}Proportion of 5\rq-UTRs were calculated for each gene decile for genes lacking a second 5\rq-UTR within the gene boundaries.}}
        \label{fig:utr_nosecond}
    \end{figure}
    

    %Figure 5'-UTR examples
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{25utr.png}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Examples of Genes Containing Secondary 5'-UTRs:\\} RAB42, GLB3, and CLCNKB are examples of genes with alternative 5'-UTRs within the gene boundaries. RAB42 contains the secondary 5'-UTR in the 10 - 20\% bin, GLB3 in the 20 - 30\% bin, and CLCNKB in the 30-40\% bin. Orange: Gene classified as containing the primary UTR; Green: Gene classified as containing the secondary UTR.}}
        \label{fig:25utr}
    \end{figure}
    

Once genes with 2$^\circ$  5\rq-UTRs were identified, they were further grouped into subsets based on the decile location of the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs. For example, Group I genes contained all 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs in the first decile. Group II contained genes where the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs were in the second decile, and so on for all ten deciles (figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}). The distribution of  5\rq -UTRs within these genes are presented in figure \ref{fig:utr_second}. As expected, the number of 5\rq -UTRs increased in the decile containing the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR (normalized decile 0). The frequencies of all AS and S L1 and Alu were calculated within these gene groups and compared to expectation based on genes lacking any 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs. 

    
    %Figure 5'-UTR Analysis
    \begin{figure}[!h]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{5utr_diag.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Design for analyzing the impact of internal 5\rq-UTRs on RT density\\}Light green: Genes with only one 5'-UTR located between the transcription start (TSS) and transcription stop site. Dark green: Genes with a second 5\rq-UTR between TSS and transcription stop. Red bar: Decile containing the second 5\rq-UTR. The UTR in the 5\rq-most position was defined as the primary (1$^\circ$) 5\rq-UTR. Dark green genes were grouped by the decile (bin) containing the secondary (2$^\circ$) UTR. All groups were then normalized by the secondary 5\rq-UTR position by defining the bin that contained the 2$^\circ$ UTR as 0. Each bin downstream was defined consecutively as 1, 2, ... 7, and each bin upstream was defined as -1, -2,...-7.}}
        \label{fig:5utr_diag}
    \end{figure}


    
    %Figure 5'-UTR in genes with secondary 5'UTRs
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{utr_second.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Distribution of 5\rq-UTRs in genes containing 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs\\}Proportion of 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTRs were calculated after normalization as described in figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}. Decile 0 is the decile containing the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR. All negative deciles are upstream of the 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR, and all positive deciles are downstream.}}
        \label{fig:utr_second}
    \end{figure}
    


\subsubsection{\textit{Alu}}
AS Alu in genes containing 2$^\circ$ 5\rq -UTRs were similar in density to the AS Alu in genes lacking 2$^\circ$ UTRs (figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASalu}). The normalized, 0, decile containing the 2$^\circ$ UTR (mean: 0.049) was significantly reduced compared to the same decile in genes without 2$^\circ$ UTRs (mean: 0.058) (Student's t-test p < 0.039). S Alu showed a slight trend towards an increase over expectation upstream of the 0 decile (figure \ref{fig:2utr_Salu}). The 0 decile, however, was significantly decreased beyond expectation (mean second UTR: 0.41 ; mean no second UTR: 0.46 ; Student's t-test p < 5.2e-04) similar to the AS Alu. 

    %Figure 5'-UTR AS Alu
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_ASalu.pdf}
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{2utr_ASalu.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Change in AS Alu density in the presence of a 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR\\}Proportion of 2$^\circ$ AS Alu proportions were calculated as described in figure \ref{fig:5utr_diag}. All proportions were normalized by the expected proportion based on RefSeq genes that have no 2$^\circ$ within the gene boundaries. }}
        \label{fig:2utr_ASalu}
    \end{figure}
    
    
    
    %Figure 5'-UTR S Alu
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_Salu.pdf}
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{2utr_Salu.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Change in S Alu density in the presence of a secondary 5\rq-UTR\\}Calculated similarly to figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASalu}}}
        \label{fig:2utr_Salu}
    \end{figure}
    
    
\subsubsection{\textit{L1}}
The distribution of AS L1 within genes containing 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR was somewhat similar to that observed with AS Alu (figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASl1}). Interestingly, there was a slight decrease in L1 density upstream of the 0 decile for AS L1 in genes containing a 2$^\circ$ 5\rq-UTR, followed by an increase, though this decrease was not significant. The 0 decile was significantly reduced over expectation (mean second UTR: 0.057 ; mean no second UTR: 0.071 ; Student's t-test p < 0.007), although the S L1 were not significantly reduced (p = 0.47) (figure \ref{fig:2utr_Sl1}). These results showed that there was a decrease of L1 and Alu in the presence of a 5\rq-UTR. 
    
        %Figure 5'-UTR AS L1
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_ASl1.pdf}
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{2utr_ASl1.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Change in AS L1 density in the presence of a secondary 5\rq-UTR\\}Calculated similarly to figure \ref{fig:2utr_ASalu}}}
        \label{fig:2utr_ASl1}
    \end{figure}
    
    
    
    %Figure 5'-UTR S L1
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{2utr_Sl1.pdf}
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{2utr_Sl1.pdf}
