%These motifs were counted in intergenic Alu and normalized by the total number of intergenic Alu (figure \ref{fig:aluintmotif}). These values were calculated to act as a reference point for examining the changes in motif distribution based on placement of the element. As expected, based on the load of CpGs within the Alu consensus sequence, CpGs were the most prevalent motif in intergenic Alu. The next most prevalent motifs were PITX2, LYF1, and OTX2. This was also expected based on the presence of these elements with in every consensus sequence tested. 
%         
%    %Figure Alu motifs intergenic
%    \begin{figure}[!ht]
%        \centering
%        \includegraphics[width=0.65\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{alu_int_motif.pdf}
%       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{}}}
%        \label{fig:aluintmotif}
%    \end{figure}

The proportions of motifs within intergenic Alu were used to normalize the proportions of binding motifs identified within genes (figure \ref{fig:alumotifs}). To correct for differences in the total number of Alu within different regions of the genome, the count of motifs were first normalized by the number of elements within each region analyzed. After this normalization procedure, the proportion of any given motif was effected more by the placement within a gene, than the sequence of the motif. For example, all of the motifs located within AS Alu had values above 1.2, independent of the type of motif. Similarly, all of the motifs within S Alu had values below 0.8.


    %Figure Alu motifs 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{alumotifs.pdf}
         \includegraphics[scale=1, width=\textwidth]{alumotifs.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Presence of Alu-contained protein-binding motifs within genes\\}Protein binding motifs were examined for their presence within Alu both in genes and intergenically. The y-axis represents the ratio of the presence within genes to the presence intergenically. Alu within genes were separated into categories based on the linear decline of AS-bias. AS\_5prime: Antisense Alu in the 10-20\% decile; S\_5prime: Sense Alu in the 10-20\% decile; AS\_3prime: Antisense Alu in the 80-90\% decile; S\_3prime: Sense Alu in the 80-90\% decile. The RNA Polymerase III A-box promoter (Pol3) is highlighted by an orange dashed box.}}
        \label{fig:alumotifs}
    \end{figure}
    
ANOVA was performed to determine if the effect of placement (i.e: sense, antisense, in genes, 5\rq -, 3\rq -) was significantly more than the effect of the sequence of the motif (equations \ref{Alu1} and \ref{Alu2}). Placement did indeed have a more significant effect on the proportion of motif than the sequence of motif (p$_{placement}$ < 2.2e-16; p$_{sequence}$ = 0.99). 

   %Linear Regression Equation 1 : Alu motif
    \begin{equation}
    \label{Alu1}
        y  = \beta _{o} + \beta motif_{i} + ... + \beta motif_{n} + \epsilon
    \end{equation}

    %Linear Regression Equation 2 : Alu position
    \begin{equation}
    \label{Alu2}
        y  = \beta _{o} + \beta position_{i} + ... + \beta position_{n} + \epsilon 
    \end{equation}

    
\subsection{Protein Binding Motifs in L1}
The proportions of motifs in intergenic L1 were compared to the proportions within genes. As before, the values were normalized by the total number of elements in the respective region prior to comparison versus intergenic L1. Contrary to the pattern seen with Alu, L1 showed no trend of enrichment based on the placement within the gene. Instead the sequence of the motif had a significant effect on the proportion of motifs (p$_{placement}$ = 0.78; p$_{sequence}$ < 3.56e-13). Furthermore, unlike Alu, all motifs within L1 were reduced in genes compared to intergenically. The largest depletion present was of the SRY motif. 

    %%Figure L1 motifs intergenic
    %\begin{figure}[!ht]
    %    \centering
    %    \includegraphics[width=0.65\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1_int_motif.pdf}
    %   \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{}}}
    %    \label{fig:l1intmotif}
    %\end{figure}


    %Figure L1 motifs
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
       %\includegraphics[width=1.2\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1motifs.pdf}
       \includegraphics[scale=1, width=\textwidth]{l1motifs.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Presence of L1-contained protein-binding motifs within genes\\}Protein binding motifs were examined similarly to those within Alu (figure \ref{fig:alumotifs}).}}
        \label{fig:l1motifs}
    \end{figure}

These results indicated that the sequence of both Alu and L1 were differentially maintained in genes versus intergenically. Binding motifs contained within Alu were reduced in a pattern similar to the distribution of the whole elements. Conversely, binding motifs within L1 were reduced depending on the sequence of the motif. 

%Example of the Polyadenylation Signal and PolIII 
\subsection{Conservation at the Basepair Level of Binding Motifs}

    %Figure l1 polyA
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1polyA.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Basewise conservation of polyadenylation signals within S and AS L1\\}
       Basewise conservation scores were taken from the phyloP conservation scores, where positive values indicate potential positive selection, and negative values indicate possible negative selection. The scores of each bp were calculated for intergenic L1, AS L1, and S L1. AS (pink dots) and S (blue dots) L1 were then normalized versus the intergenic values. 
       }}
        \label{fig:l1polyA}
    \end{figure}
    
    %Figure alu polyA
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{alupolyA.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Baswise conservation of polyadenylation signals within S and AS Alu\\}
              Basewise conservation scores were taken from the phyloP conservation scores, where positive values indicate potential positive selection, and negative values indicate possible negative selection. The scores of each bp were calculated for intergenic Alu, AS Alu, and S Alu. AS (pink dots) and S (blue dots) Alu were then normalized versus the intergenic values.
              }}
        \label{fig:alupolyA}
    \end{figure}
    
The previous analysis examined the distribution of binding motifs by calculating the lack of motifs in the reference human genome. It was also important to analyze the distribution of binding motifs through the conservation status, which would examine the motifs that are present in the human genome. Moreover, analyzing the conservation scores would allow a base-by-base analysis of the binding motif. Conservation values used in this analysis were from the phyloP basewise conservation scores, where positive values indicated evidence of positive selection, and negative values indicated evidence of purifying selection. Importantly, conservation was only calculated within regions that matched the binding motif within the human reference sequence. Therefore, as opposed to the previous analysis which modeled the loss of binding motifs in the human reference, this calculation analyzed the individual basepairs within motifs that were present in humans but potentially lost in non-human primates.

Since the polyadenylation sequence was present within both Alu and L1 consensus sequences, this was the first motif analyzed. Basewise conservation scores were averaged for each base within the polyadenylation sequence of either L1 (figure \ref{fig:l1polyA}) or Alu (figure \ref{fig:alupolyA}). L1 and Alu elements were first separated into AS and S elements before the conservation scores were calculated. Interestingly, both Alu and L1 showed a decrease in conservation at the central T base. Moreover, polyadenylation signals of L1 in the sense orientation had a lower conservation score on average than those of AS oriented L1. 

    
        %Figure alu pol3
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        %\includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{alupol3.pdf}
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{alupol3.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Basewise conservation of Pol-III A-box region in AS and S Alu \\} Conservation scores were derived from phyloP conservation scores where a positive value indicates positive selection and a negative value indicates possible negative selection. AS and S values were normalized by intergenic values}}
        \label{fig:alupol3}
    \end{figure}
   
Conservation of the Alu-specific Pol-III A-box (figure \ref{fig: alupol3}) was also examined in both the AS and S orientations. The Pol-III A-box is required for transcription and retrotransposition of Alu. When normalized versus intergenic values, there was no major difference between AS and S conservation signals, similar to what was observed for the polyadenylation signal within Alu.

There are four CpGs within the Pol-III A-box consensus sequence. The cytosine within a CpG context is more likely to undergo mutation than other nucleotides due to the common deamination of 5-methylcytosine. Surprisingly, only one of the four CpGs present within the queried sequence (position 20) was less conserved than the same position intergenically. Two bp in the Pol-III sequence were more highly conserved within genes than intergenically. These were the cytosine at position 3 and guanine at position 15.

These results indicated that each position within a RT-contained binding motif had a different expectation of conservation. Interestingly, the polyadenylation sequence, had a similar dynamic of conservation  independent of the element within which it resided. Moreover, the S L1 had a complete reduction of the polyadenylation signal, whereas the AS L1, S Alu, and AS Alu all had reductions only in the central thymine. This indicated that S polyadenylation signals may be strongly purified from within genes. Evidence in the literature that S L1 contribute to pre-mature polyadenylation substantiates this hypothesis \cite{Kaer2011}. 

\section{Interaction between Gene-specific and Retrotransposon-specific Variables}
    %Functional Binding Motifs Effect Maintenance, Tissue Specific
\subsection{Functional Binding Motifs Effect Maintenance, Tissue Specific}
Lastly, it was determined how the RT-specific variable of binding motifs was effected by the gene-specific variable of tissue-specific gene expression. To reduce the number of statistical tests, analysis was restricted to the deciles that contained the extremes of Alu and L1 frequency. These were deciles 2 and 9, otherwise defined as the first and last bins within the linear range of Alu/L1 frequency (section \ref{sec:as_dec}). To correct for differences in overall abundance of RTs depending on placement, motif frequencies were normalized by the count of AS or S elements within the respective bin. This was repeated separately for tissue-specific (TS) genes and house-keeping (HK) genes. 

\subsubsection{\textit{Alu}}

    %Figure Alu sense (TS / HK) motifs
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{alu_tshkmotifs_value.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Alu-contained binding motifs in tissue-specific and housekeeping genes}}}
        \label{fig:alu_tshkmotifs_value}
    \end{figure}
    
    
        %Figure Alu sense (TS / HK) motifs p-values
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{alu_tshkmotifs.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Alu-contained binding motifs in tissue-specific and housekeeping genes}}}
        \label{fig:alumotifs_tshk}
    \end{figure}

Since there was no normalization against intergenic in this analysis, the changes in proportion due to each motif was observable for this analysis (figure \ref{fig:alumotifs_tshk}). The proportion of motifs in each placement within TS genes were compared to the counterpart in HK genes. In general proportions of motifs in TS genes were larger than HK genes (87 of 140). 29 of the 140 comparisons were significant after Bonferonni correction ($\alpha$ = 3.6e-04) (figure \ref{fig:alumotifs_tshk}). Many of these comparisons were from polyadenylation sequences (N = 5 of 7 possible), and LUN1 (N = 4 of 7 possible). The majority of the significant comparisons were derived from whole gene comparisons (10 of 29 tests).

\subsubsection{\textit{L1}}

    
    %Figure L1 sense (TS / HK) motifs
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{l1_tshkmotifs_value.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{L1-contained binding motifs in tissue-specific and housekeeping genes}}}
        \label{fig:l1_tshkmotifs_value}
    \end{figure}
    
    
    %Figure L1 sense (TS / HK) motifs p-values
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[scale=1,width=\textwidth]{l1_tshkmotifs.pdf}
       \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{L1-contained binding motifs in tissue-specific and housekeeping genes}}}
        \label{fig:l1motifs_tshk}
    \end{figure}

For L1-contained motifs, all proportions of motifs were greater in TS genes than the respective placement in HK genes (56 of 56) (figure \ref{fig:l1_tshkmotifs_value}). 35 of the 56 comparisons were significant after Bonferonni correction ($\alpha$ = 8.9e-04) (figure \ref{fig:l1motifs_tshk}). The majority of the significant comparisons were within polyadenylation sequences (N = 7 of 7 possible), and the second variation of RUNX3 (N$_{b}$ = 6 of 7 possible). 
}

    
